# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pharmacophore-modeling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] In medicinal chemistry, **bioisosteres** are chemical substituents or groups with similar physical or chemical properties which produce broadly similar biological properties in the same chemical compound.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] In drug design, the purpose of exchanging one bioisostere for another is to enhance the desired biological or physical properties of a compound without making significant changes in chemical structure.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] The main use of this term and its techniques are related to pharmaceutical sciences.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] Bioisosterism is used to reduce toxicity, change bioavailability, or modify the activity of the lead compound, and may alter the metabolism of the lead.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] Classical bioisosterism was originally formulated by James Moir and refined by Irving Langmuir as a response to the observation that different atoms with the same valence electron structure had similar biological properties.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] For example, the replacement of a hydrogen atom with a fluorine atom at a site of metabolic oxidation in a drug candidate may prevent such metabolism from taking place.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] Because the fluorine atom is similar in size to the hydrogen atom the overall topology of the molecule is not significantly affected, leaving the desired biological activity unaffected.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] However, with a blocked pathway for metabolism, the drug candidate may have a longer half-life.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] Another example is seen in a series of anti-bacterial chalcones.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] By modifying certain substituents, the pharmacological activity of the chalcone and its toxicity are also modified.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] Non-classical bioisosteres may differ in a multitude of ways from classical bioisosteres, but retain the focus on providing similar sterics and electronic profile to the original functional group.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] For example, a chloride -Cl group may often be replaced by a trifluoromethyl -CF3 group or by a cyano -C≡N group.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] Depending on the particular molecule used, the substitution may result in little change in activity, or either increased or decreased affinity or efficacy - depending on what factors are important for ligand binding to the target protein.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] Bioisosteres of some patented compounds can be discovered automatically and used to circumvent Markush structure patent claims.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/bioisostere] It has been proposed that key force field features, that is the pharmacophore, be patented instead.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] The FEP method was introduced by Robert W.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] where *T* is the temperature, *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, and the angular brackets denote an average over a simulation run for state **A**.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] In practice, one runs a normal simulation for state **A**, but each time a new configuration is accepted, the energy for state **B** is also computed.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] The difference between states **A** and **B** may be in the atom types involved, in which case the Δ*F* obtained is for "mutating" one molecule onto another, or it may be a difference of geometry, in which case one obtains a free-energy map along one or more reaction coordinates.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] This free-energy map is also known as a *potential of mean force* (PMF).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] Free-energy perturbation calculations only converge properly when the difference between the two states is small enough (the phase space of the two states overlap).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] In practice, the perturbation is divided into a series of smaller, discrete intermediate FEP windows defined by the coupling parameter $\lambda$ .
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] Since there is no need for constant communication between the simulation for one window and the next, the process can be trivially parallelized by running each window on a different CPU, in what is known as an "embarrassingly parallel" setup.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] FEP calculations have been used for studying host–guest binding energetics, pKa predictions, solvent effects on reactions, and enzymatic reactions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] Other applications are the virtual screening of ligands in drug discovery, *in silico* mutagenesis studies and antibody affinity maturation.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] For the study of reactions it is often necessary to involve a quantum-mechanical (QM) representation of the reaction center because the molecular mechanics (MM) force fields used for FEP simulations cannot handle breaking bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] A hybrid method that has the advantages of both QM and MM calculations is called QM/MM.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] An alternative to free-energy perturbation for computing potentials of mean force in chemical space is thermodynamic integration.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] Another alternative, which is probably more efficient, is the Bennett acceptance ratio method.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] Adaptations to FEP exist which attempt to apportion free-energy changes to subsections of the chemical structure.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] Since free energy is a state function, the total free energy change between two states are independent of the path taken.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] Using FEP calculations and closed thermodynamic cycles, it is possible to calculate the relative change in free energy, for example comparing two ligands A and B binding to a target substrate.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/free-energy-perturbation] FEP methods have been implemented in several molecular dynamics software packages.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Unlike simple dipole–dipole interactions, hydrogen bonding arises from charge transfer (nB → σ*AH), orbital interactions, and quantum mechanical delocalization, making it a **resonance-assisted interaction** rather than a mere electrostatic attraction.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The general notation for hydrogen bonding is **Dn−H···Ac**, where the solid line represents a polar covalent bond, and the three dots indicate the hydrogen bond.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] **Hydrogen bond donors** have a protic hydrogen attached to an electronegative atom such as nitrogen (N), oxygen (O), and fluorine (F).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] **Hydrogen bond acceptors** have a lone pair of electrons, such as the nitrogen atom of amines and amides and the oxygen atom of carboxylates and water.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The term "hydrogen bond" is generally used for well-defined, localized interactions with significant charge transfer and orbital overlap, such as those in DNA base pairing or ice.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In contrast, "hydrogen-bonding interactions" is a broader term used when the interaction is weaker, more dynamic, or delocalized, such as in liquid water, supramolecular assemblies (e.g.: lipid membranes, protein-protein interactions), or weak C-H···O interactions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This distinction is particularly relevant in structural biology, materials science, and computational chemistry, where hydrogen bonding spans a continuum from weak van der Waals-like interactions to nearly covalent bonding.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding can occur between separate molecules (intermolecular) or within different parts of the same molecule (intramolecular).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Its strength varies considerably, depending on geometry, environment, and the donor-acceptor pair, typically ranging from 4.2 to 167.4 kJ/mol (1 to 40 kcal/mol).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This places hydrogen bonds stronger than van der Waals interactions but generally weaker than covalent or ionic bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding plays a fundamental role in chemistry, biology, and materials science.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] It is responsible for the anomalously high boiling point of water, the stabilization of protein and nucleic acid structures, and key properties of materials like paper, wool, and hydrogels.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In biological systems, hydrogen bonds mediate molecular recognition, enzyme catalysis, and DNA replication, while in materials science, they contribute to self-assembly, adhesion, and supramolecular organization.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In a hydrogen bond, the electronegative atom not covalently attached to the hydrogen is named the proton acceptor, whereas the one covalently bound to the hydrogen is named the proton donor.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This nomenclature is recommended by the IUPAC.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The hydrogen of the donor is protic and therefore can act as a Lewis acid and the acceptor is the Lewis base.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds are represented as H···Y system, where the dots represent the hydrogen bond.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Liquids that display hydrogen bonding (such as water) are called **associated liquids**.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds arise from a combination of electrostatics (multipole-multipole and multipole-induced multipole interactions), covalency (charge transfer by orbital overlap), and dispersion (London forces).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In weaker hydrogen bonds, hydrogen atoms tend to bond to elements such as sulfur (S) or chlorine (Cl); even carbon (C) can serve as a donor, particularly when the carbon or one of its neighbors is electronegative (e.g., in chloroform, aldehydes and terminal acetylenes).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Gradually, it was recognized that there are many examples of weaker hydrogen bonding involving donor other than N, O, or F and/or acceptor Ac with electronegativity approaching that of hydrogen (rather than being much more electronegative).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Although weak (about 4.2 kJ/mol (1 kcal/mol)), "non-traditional" hydrogen bonding interactions are ubiquitous and influence structures of many kinds of materials.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The definition of hydrogen bonding has gradually broadened over time to include these weaker attractive interactions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In 2011, an IUPAC Task Group recommended a modern evidence-based definition of hydrogen bonding, which was published in the IUPAC journal *Pure and Applied Chemistry*.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds can vary in strength from weak (1–2 kJ/mol) to strong (161.5 kJ/mol in the bifluoride ion, HF2-).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The strength of intermolecular hydrogen bonds is most often evaluated by measurements of equilibria between molecules containing donor and/or acceptor units, most often in solution.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The strength of intramolecular hydrogen bonds can be studied with equilibria between conformers with and without hydrogen bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The most important method for the identification of hydrogen bonds also in complicated molecules is crystallography, sometimes also NMR-spectroscopy.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Structural details, in particular distances between donor and acceptor which are smaller than the sum of the van der Waals radii can be taken as indication of the hydrogen bond strength.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] One scheme gives the following somewhat arbitrary classification: those that are 63 to 167 kJ/mol (15 to 40 kcal/mol), 21 to 63 kJ/mol (5 to 15 kcal/mol), and 0 to 21 kJ/mol (0 to 5 kcal/mol) are considered strong, moderate, and weak, respectively.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds involving C−H bonds are both very rare and weak.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The **resonance assisted hydrogen bond** (commonly abbreviated as RAHB) is a strong type of hydrogen bond.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] It is characterized by the π-delocalization that involves the hydrogen atom and cannot be properly described by the electrostatic model alone.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This description of the hydrogen bond has been proposed to describe unusually short distances generally observed between O=C−OH··· or ···O=C−C=C−OH.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The X−H distance is typically ≈110 pm, whereas the H···Y distance is ≈160 to 200 pm.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The typical length of a hydrogen bond in water is 197 pm.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The ideal bond angle depends on the nature of the hydrogen bond donor.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Strong hydrogen bonds are revealed by downfield shifts in the 1H NMR spectrum.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] For example, the acidic proton in the enol tautomer of acetylacetone appears at ⁠ $\delta _{\text{H}}$ ⁠ 15.5, which is about 10 ppm downfield of a conventional alcohol.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In the IR spectrum, hydrogen bonding shifts the X−H stretching frequency to lower energy (i.e. the vibration frequency decreases).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This shift reflects a weakening of the X−H bond.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Certain hydrogen bonds - improper hydrogen bonds - show a blue shift of the X−H stretching frequency and a decrease in the bond length.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] H-bonds can also be measured by IR vibrational mode shifts of the acceptor.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The amide I mode of backbone carbonyls in α-helices shifts to lower frequencies when they form H-bonds with side-chain hydroxyl groups.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The dynamics of hydrogen bond structures in water can be probed by this OH stretching vibration.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The sudden weakening of hydrogen bonds during the solid-solid phase transition seems to be coupled with the onset of orientational or rotational disorder of the ions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding is of persistent theoretical interest.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] According to a modern description O:H−O integrates both the intermolecular O:H lone pair ":" nonbond and the intramolecular H−O polar-covalent bond associated with O−O repulsive coupling.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Quantum chemical calculations of the relevant interresidue potential constants (compliance constants) revealed large differences between individual H bonds of the same type.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] For example, the central interresidue N−H···N hydrogen bond between guanine and cytosine is much stronger in comparison to the N−H···N bond between the adenine-thymine pair.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Theoretically, the bond strength of the hydrogen bonds can be assessed using NCI index, non-covalent interactions index, which allows a visualization of these non-covalent interactions, as its name indicates, using the electron density of the system.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Interpretations of the anisotropies in the Compton profile of ordinary ice claim that the hydrogen bond is partly covalent.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] However, this interpretation was challenged and subsequently clarified.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Most generally, the hydrogen bond can be viewed as a metric-dependent electrostatic scalar field between two or more intermolecular bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This is slightly different from the intramolecular bound states of, for example, covalent or ionic bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] However, hydrogen bonding is generally still a bound state phenomenon, since the interaction energy has a net negative sum.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The initial theory of hydrogen bonding proposed by Linus Pauling suggested that the hydrogen bonds had a partial covalent nature.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This interpretation remained controversial until NMR techniques demonstrated information transfer between hydrogen-bonded nuclei, a feat that would only be possible if the hydrogen bond contained some covalent character.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The concept of hydrogen bonding once was challenging.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Winmill with the first mention of the hydrogen bond, in 1912.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Moore and Winmill used the hydrogen bond to account for the fact that trimethylammonium hydroxide is a weaker base than tetramethylammonium hydroxide.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The description of hydrogen bonding in its better-known setting, water, came some years later, in 1920, from Latimer and Rodebush.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In that paper, Latimer and Rodebush cited the work of a fellow scientist at their laboratory, Maurice Loyal Huggins, saying, "Mr.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] An ubiquitous example of a hydrogen bond is found between water molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In a discrete water molecule, there are two hydrogen atoms and one oxygen atom.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The simplest case is a pair of water molecules with one hydrogen bond between them, which is called the water dimer and is often used as a model system.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] When more molecules are present, as is the case with liquid water, more bonds are possible because the oxygen of one water molecule has two lone pairs of electrons, each of which can form a hydrogen bond with a hydrogen on another water molecule.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This can repeat such that every water molecule is H-bonded with up to four other molecules, as shown in the figure (two through its two lone pairs, and two through its two hydrogen atoms).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding strongly affects the crystal structure of ice, helping to create an open hexagonal lattice.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The density of ice is less than the density of water at the same temperature; thus, the solid phase of water floats on the liquid, unlike most other substances.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Liquid water's high boiling point is due to the high number of hydrogen bonds each molecule can form, relative to its low molecular mass.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Owing to the difficulty of breaking these bonds, water has a very high boiling point, melting point, and viscosity compared to otherwise similar liquids not conjoined by hydrogen bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Water is unique because its oxygen atom has two lone pairs and two hydrogen atoms, meaning that the total number of bonds of a water molecule is up to four.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The number of hydrogen bonds formed by a molecule of liquid water fluctuates with time and temperature.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] From TIP4P liquid water simulations at 25 °C, it was estimated that each water molecule participates in an average of 3.59 hydrogen bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] At 100 °C, this number decreases to 3.24 due to the increased molecular motion and decreased density, while at 0 °C, the average number of hydrogen bonds increases to 3.69.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Another study found a much smaller number of hydrogen bonds: 2.357 at 25 °C.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Defining and counting the hydrogen bonds is not straightforward however.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Because water may form hydrogen bonds with solute proton donors and acceptors, it may competitively inhibit the formation of solute intermolecular or intramolecular hydrogen bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Consequently, hydrogen bonds between or within solute molecules dissolved in water are almost always unfavorable relative to hydrogen bonds between water and the donors and acceptors for hydrogen bonds on those solutes.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds between water molecules have an average lifetime of 10−11 seconds, or 10 picoseconds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] A single hydrogen atom can participate in two hydrogen bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This type of bonding is called "bifurcated" (split in two or "two-forked").
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] It can exist, for instance, in complex organic molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] It has been suggested that a bifurcated hydrogen atom is an essential step in water reorientation.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Acceptor-type hydrogen bonds (terminating on an oxygen's lone pairs) are more likely to form bifurcation (it is called overcoordinated oxygen, OCO) than are donor-type hydrogen bonds, beginning on the same oxygen atom's hydrogen atoms.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] For example, hydrogen fluoride—which has three lone pairs on the F atom but only one H atom—can form only two bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Ammonia has the opposite problem: three hydrogen atoms but only one lone pair.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonding plays an important role in determining the three-dimensional structures and the properties adopted by many proteins.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Compared to the C−C, C−O, and C−N bonds that comprise most polymers, hydrogen bonds are far weaker, perhaps 5% as strong.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Thus, hydrogen bonds can be broken by chemical or mechanical means while retaining the basic structure of the polymer backbone.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This hierarchy of bond strengths (covalent bonds being stronger than hydrogen-bonds being stronger than van der Waals forces) is relevant in the properties of many materials.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In these macromolecules, bonding between parts of the same macromolecule cause it to fold into a specific shape, which helps determine the molecule's physiological or biochemical role.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] For example, the double helical structure of DNA is due largely to hydrogen bonding between its base pairs (as well as pi stacking interactions), which link one complementary strand to the other and enable replication.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In the secondary structure of proteins, hydrogen bonds form between the backbone oxygens and amide hydrogens.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] When the spacing of the amino acid residues participating in a hydrogen bond occurs regularly between positions *i* and *i* + 4, an alpha helix is formed.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] When the spacing is less, between positions *i* and *i* + 3, then a 310 helix is formed.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] When two strands are joined by hydrogen bonds involving alternating residues on each participating strand, a beta sheet is formed.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds also play a part in forming the tertiary structure of protein through interaction of R-groups.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Bifurcated H-bond systems are common in alpha-helical transmembrane proteins between the backbone amide C=O of residue *i* as the H-bond acceptor and two H-bond donors from residue *i* + 4: the backbone amide N−H and a side-chain hydroxyl or thiol H+.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The energy preference of the bifurcated H-bond hydroxyl or thiol system is −14 or 167 kJ/mol (−3.4 or 40 kcal/mol) respectively.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This type of bifurcated H-bond provides an intrahelical H-bonding partner for polar side-chains, such as serine, threonine, and cysteine within the hydrophobic membrane environments.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The role of hydrogen bonds in protein folding has also been linked to osmolyte-induced protein stabilization.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Protective osmolytes, such as trehalose and sorbitol, shift the protein folding equilibrium toward the folded state, in a concentration dependent manner.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] While the prevalent explanation for osmolyte action relies on excluded volume effects that are entropic in nature, circular dichroism (CD) experiments have shown osmolyte to act through an enthalpic effect.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The molecular mechanism for their role in protein stabilization is still not well established, though several mechanisms have been proposed.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Computer molecular dynamics simulations suggest that osmolytes stabilize proteins by modifying the hydrogen bonds in the protein hydration layer.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Several studies have shown that hydrogen bonds play an important role for the stability between subunits in multimeric proteins.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] For example, a study of sorbitol dehydrogenase displayed an important hydrogen bonding network which stabilizes the tetrameric quaternary structure within the mammalian sorbitol dehydrogenase protein family.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] A protein backbone hydrogen bond incompletely shielded from water attack is a dehydron.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Dehydrons promote the removal of water through proteins or ligand binding.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The exogenous dehydration enhances the electrostatic interaction between the amide and carbonyl groups by de-shielding their partial charges.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Furthermore, the dehydration stabilizes the hydrogen bond by destabilizing the nonbonded state consisting of dehydrated isolated charges.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Wool, being a protein fibre, is held together by hydrogen bonds, causing wool to recoil when stretched.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] However, washing at high temperatures can permanently break the hydrogen bonds and a garment may permanently lose its shape.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The properties of many polymers are affected by hydrogen bonds within and/or between the chains.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Prominent examples include cellulose and its derived fibers, such as cotton and flax.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In nylon, hydrogen bonds between carbonyl and the amide N*H* effectively link adjacent chains, which gives the material mechanical strength.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen bonds also affect the aramid fibre, where hydrogen bonds stabilize the linear chains laterally.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The chain axes are aligned along the fibre axis, making the fibres extremely stiff and strong.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Hydrogen-bond networks make both polymers sensitive to humidity levels in the atmosphere because water molecules can diffuse into the surface and disrupt the network.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Some polymers are more sensitive than others.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Thus nylons are more sensitive than aramids, and nylon 6 more sensitive than nylon-11.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] A symmetric hydrogen bond is a special type of hydrogen bond in which the proton is spaced exactly halfway between two identical atoms.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The strength of the bond to each of those atoms is equal.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] It is an example of a three-center four-electron bond.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] This type of bond is much stronger than a "normal" hydrogen bond.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The effective bond order is 0.5, so its strength is comparable to a covalent bond.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] It is seen in ice at high pressure, and also in the solid phase of many anhydrous acids such as hydrofluoric acid and formic acid at high pressure.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] It is also seen in the bifluoride ion [F···H···F]−.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Due to severe steric constraint, the protonated form of Proton Sponge (1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene) and its derivatives also have symmetric hydrogen bonds ([N···H···N]+), although in the case of protonated Proton Sponge, the assembly is bent.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The hydrogen bond can be compared with the closely related dihydrogen bond, which is also an intermolecular bonding interaction involving hydrogen atoms.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] These structures have been known for some time, and well characterized by crystallography; however, an understanding of their relationship to the conventional hydrogen bond, ionic bond, and covalent bond remains unclear.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Generally, the hydrogen bond is characterized by a proton acceptor that is a lone pair of electrons in nonmetallic atoms (most notably in the nitrogen, and chalcogen groups).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In some cases, these proton acceptors may be pi-bonds or metal complexes.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] In the dihydrogen bond, however, a metal hydride serves as a proton acceptor, thus forming a hydrogen-hydrogen interaction.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Neutron diffraction has shown that the molecular geometry of these complexes is similar to hydrogen bonds, in that the bond length is very adaptable to the metal complex/hydrogen donor system.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] The hydrogen bond is relevant to drug design.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] According to Lipinski's rule of five the majority of orally active drugs have no more than five hydrogen bond donors and fewer than ten hydrogen bond acceptors.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] These interactions exist between nitrogen–hydrogen and oxygen–hydrogen centers.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/hydrogen-bond] Many drugs do not, however, obey these "rules".
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Molecular geometry influences several properties of a substance including its reactivity, polarity, phase of matter, color, magnetism and biological activity.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The angles between bonds that an atom forms depend only weakly on the rest of a molecule, i.e. they can be understood as approximately local and hence transferable properties.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The molecular geometry can be determined by various spectroscopic methods and diffraction methods.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] IR, microwave and Raman spectroscopy can give information about the molecule geometry from the details of the vibrational and rotational absorbance detected by these techniques.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] X-ray crystallography, neutron diffraction and electron diffraction can give molecular structure for crystalline solids based on the distance between nuclei and concentration of electron density.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Gas electron diffraction can be used for small molecules in the gas phase.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] NMR and FRET methods can be used to determine complementary information including relative distances, dihedral angles, angles, and connectivity.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Molecular geometries are best determined at low temperature because at higher temperatures the molecular structure is averaged over more accessible geometries (see next section).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Larger molecules often exist in multiple stable geometries (conformational isomerism) that are close in energy on the potential energy surface.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Geometries can also be computed by ab initio quantum chemistry methods to high accuracy.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The molecular geometry can be different as a solid, in solution, and as a gas.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The position of each atom is determined by the nature of the chemical bonds by which it is connected to its neighboring atoms.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The molecular geometry can be described by the positions of these atoms in space, evoking bond lengths of two joined atoms, bond angles of three connected atoms, and torsion angles (dihedral angles) of three consecutive bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Since the motions of the atoms in a molecule are determined by quantum mechanics, "motion" must be defined in a quantum mechanical way.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The overall (external) quantum mechanical motions translation and rotation hardly change the geometry of the molecule.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The molecular vibrations are harmonic (at least to good approximation), and the atoms oscillate about their equilibrium positions, even at the absolute zero of temperature.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] At higher temperatures the vibrational modes may be thermally excited (in a classical interpretation one expresses this by stating that "the molecules will vibrate faster"), but they oscillate still around the recognizable geometry of the molecule.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] To get a feeling for the probability that the vibration of molecule may be thermally excited, we inspect the Boltzmann factor *β* ≡ exp(−⁠Δ*E*/*kT*⁠), where Δ*E* is the excitation energy of the vibrational mode, *k* the Boltzmann constant and *T* the absolute temperature.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] (The reciprocal centimeter is an energy unit that is commonly used in infrared spectroscopy; 1 cm−1 corresponds to 1.23984×10−4 eV).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] When an excitation energy is 500 cm−1, then about 8.9 percent of the molecules are thermally excited at room temperature.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] To put this in perspective: the lowest excitation vibrational energy in water is the bending mode (about 1600 cm−1).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Thus, at room temperature less than 0.07 percent of all the molecules of a given amount of water will vibrate faster than at absolute zero.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] As stated above, rotation hardly influences the molecular geometry.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] But, as a quantum mechanical motion, it is thermally excited at relatively (as compared to vibration) low temperatures.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] From a classical point of view it can be stated that at higher temperatures more molecules will rotate faster, which implies that they have higher angular velocity and angular momentum.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] In quantum mechanical language: more eigenstates of higher angular momentum become thermally populated with rising temperatures.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Typical rotational excitation energies are on the order of a few cm−1.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The results of many spectroscopic experiments are broadened because they involve an averaging over rotational states.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] It is often difficult to extract geometries from spectra at high temperatures, because the number of rotational states probed in the experimental averaging increases with increasing temperature.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Thus, many spectroscopic observations can only be expected to yield reliable molecular geometries at temperatures close to absolute zero, because at higher temperatures too many higher rotational states are thermally populated.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Molecules, by definition, are most often held together with covalent bonds involving single, double, and/or triple bonds, where a "bond" is a shared pair of electrons (the other method of bonding between atoms is called ionic bonding and involves a positive cation and a negative anion).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Molecular geometries can be specified in terms of 'bond lengths', 'bond angles' and 'torsional angles'.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The bond length is defined to be the average distance between the nuclei of two atoms bonded together in any given molecule.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] A bond angle is the angle formed between three atoms across at least two bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] For four atoms bonded together in a chain, the torsional angle is the angle between the plane formed by the first three atoms and the plane formed by the last three atoms.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] There exists a mathematical relationship among the bond angles for one central atom and four peripheral atoms (labeled 1 through 4) expressed by the following determinant.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] This constraint removes one degree of freedom from the choices of (originally) six free bond angles to leave only five choices of bond angles.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Molecular geometry is determined by the quantum mechanical behavior of the electrons.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] Using the valence bond approximation this can be understood by the type of bonds between the atoms that make up the molecule.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] When atoms interact to form a chemical bond, the atomic orbitals of each atom are said to combine in a process called orbital hybridisation.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The two most common types of bonds are sigma bonds (usually formed by hybrid orbitals) and pi bonds (formed by unhybridized p orbitals for atoms of main group elements).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The geometry can also be understood by molecular orbital theory where the electrons are delocalised.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] An understanding of the wavelike behavior of electrons in atoms and molecules is the subject of quantum chemistry.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] A bond angle is the geometric angle between two adjacent bonds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The bond angles in the table below are ideal angles from the simple VSEPR theory, followed by the actual angle for the example given in the following column where this differs.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] For many cases, such as trigonal pyramidal and bent, the actual angle for the example differs from the ideal angle, and examples differ by different amounts.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] For example, the angle in H2S (92°) differs from the tetrahedral angle by much more than the angle for H2O (104.48°) does.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The greater the number of lone pairs contained in a molecule, the smaller the angles between the atoms of that molecule.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/molecular-geometry] The VSEPR theory predicts that lone pairs repel each other, thus pushing the different atoms away from them.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] In medicinal chemistry and molecular biology, a **pharmacophore** is an abstract description of molecular features that are necessary for molecular recognition of a ligand by a biological macromolecule.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] IUPAC defines a pharmacophore to be "an ensemble of steric and electronic features that is necessary to ensure the optimal supramolecular interactions with a specific biological target and to trigger (or block) its biological response".
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] A pharmacophore model explains how structurally diverse ligands can bind to a common receptor site.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Typical pharmacophore features include hydrophobic centroids, aromatic rings, hydrogen bond acceptors or donors, cations, and anions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] These pharmacophore points may be located on the ligand itself or may be projected points presumed to be located in the receptor.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] The features need to match different chemical groups with similar properties, in order to identify novel ligands.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Ligand-receptor interactions are typically "polar positive", "polar negative" or "hydrophobic".
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] A well-defined pharmacophore model includes both hydrophobic volumes and hydrogen bond vectors.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] **Conformational analysis** – Generate a set of low energy conformations that is likely to contain the bioactive conformation for each of the selected molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] **Molecular superimposition** – Superimpose ("fit") all combinations of the low-energy conformations of the molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Similar (bioisosteric) functional groups common to all molecules in the set might be fitted (*e.g.*, phenyl rings or carboxylic acid groups).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] The set of conformations (one conformation from each active molecule) that results in the best fit is presumed to be the active conformation.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] **Abstraction** – Transform the superimposed molecules into an abstract representation.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] For example, superimposed phenyl rings might be referred to more conceptually as an 'aromatic ring' pharmacophore element.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Likewise, hydroxy groups could be designated as a 'hydrogen-bond donor/acceptor' pharmacophore element.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] **Validation** – A pharmacophore model is a *hypothesis* accounting for the observed biological activities of a set of molecules that bind to a common biological target.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] The model is only valid insofar as it is able to account for differences in biological activity of a range of molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] As the biological activities of new molecules become available, the pharmacophore model can be updated to further refine it.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] In modern computational chemistry, pharmacophores are used to define the essential features of one or more molecules with the same biological activity.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] A database of diverse chemical compounds can then be searched for more molecules which share the same features arranged in the same relative orientation.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Pharmacophores are also used as the starting point for developing 3D-QSAR models.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Such tools and a related concept of "privileged structures", which are "defined as molecular frameworks which are able of providing useful ligands for more than one type of receptor or enzyme target by judicious structural modifications", aid in drug discovery.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Historically, the modern idea of pharmacophore was popularized by Lemont Kier, who mentions the concept in 1967 and uses the term in a publication in 1971.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] Shueler, in a 1960s book, uses the expression "pharmacophoric moiety" that corresponds to the modern concept.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] The development of the concept is often erroneously accredited to Paul Ehrlich.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/pharmacophore] However neither the alleged source nor any of his other works mention the term "pharmacophore" or make use of the concept.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] In molecular physics and chemistry, the **van der Waals force** (sometimes **van der Waals' force**) is a distance-dependent interaction between atoms or molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Unlike ionic or covalent bonds, these attractions do not result from a chemical electronic bond; they are comparatively weak and therefore more susceptible to disturbance.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The van der Waals force quickly vanishes at longer distances between interacting molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Named after Dutch physicist Johannes Diderik van der Waals, the Van der Waals force plays a fundamental role in fields as diverse as supramolecular chemistry, structural biology, polymer science, nanotechnology, surface science, and condensed matter physics.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] It also underlies many properties of organic compounds and molecular solids, including their solubility in polar and non-polar media.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] If no other force is present, the distance between atoms at which the force becomes repulsive rather than attractive as the atoms approach one another is called the **van der Waals contact distance**; this phenomenon results from the mutual repulsion between the atoms' electron clouds.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces include attraction and repulsions between atoms, molecules, as well as other intermolecular forces.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] They differ from covalent and ionic bonding in that they are caused by correlations in the fluctuating polarizations of nearby particles (a consequence of quantum dynamics).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The force results from a transient shift in electron density.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Specifically, the electron density may temporarily shift to be greater on one side of the nucleus.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] This shift generates a transient charge which a nearby atom can be attracted to or repelled by.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The force is repulsive at very short distances, reaches zero at an equilibrium distance characteristic for each atom, or molecule, and becomes attractive for distances larger than the equilibrium distance.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] For individual atoms, the equilibrium distance is between 0.3 nm and 0.5 nm, depending on the atomic-specific diameter.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] When the interatomic distance is greater than 1.0 nm the force is not strong enough to be easily observed as it decreases as a function of distance *r* approximately with the 7th power (~*r*−7).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces are often among the weakest chemical forces.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] For example, the pairwise attractive van der Waals interaction energy between H (hydrogen) atoms in different H2 molecules equals 0.06 kJ/mol (0.6 meV) and the pairwise attractive interaction energy between O (oxygen) atoms in different O2 molecules equals 0.44 kJ/mol (4.6 meV).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The strength of van der Waals bonds increases with higher polarizability of the participating atoms.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] For example, the pairwise Van der Waals interaction energy for more polarizable atoms such as S (sulfur) atoms in H2S and sulfides exceeds 1 kJ/mol (10 meV), and the pairwise interaction energy between even larger, more polarizable Xe (xenon) atoms is 2.35 kJ/mol (24.3 meV).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] These van der Waals interactions are up to 40 times stronger than in H2, which has only one valence electron, and they are still not strong enough to achieve an aggregate state other than gas for Xe (noble gas) under standard conditions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The interactions between atoms in metals can also be effectively described as van der Waals interactions and account for the observed solid aggregate state with bonding strengths comparable to covalent and ionic interactions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Accordingly, van der Waals forces can range from weak to strong interactions, and support integral structural loads when multitudes of such interactions are present.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] More broadly, intermolecular forces have several possible contributions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Attractive or repulsive electrostatic interactions between permanent charges (in the case of molecular ions), dipoles (in the case of molecules without inversion centre), quadrupoles (all molecules with symmetry lower than cubic), and in general between permanent multipoles.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] These interactions also include hydrogen bonds, cation-pi, and pi-stacking interactions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Orientation-averaged contributions from electrostatic interactions are sometimes called the Keesom interaction or Keesom force after Willem Hendrik Keesom.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Induction (also known as polarization), which is the attractive interaction between a permanent multipole on one molecule with an induced multipole on another.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] This interaction is sometimes called Debye force after Peter J.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The interactions (2) and (3) are labelled polar Interactions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Dispersion (usually named London dispersion interactions after Fritz London), which is the attractive interaction between any pair of molecules, including non-polar atoms, arising from the interactions of instantaneous multipoles.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] When to apply the term "van der Waals" force depends on the text.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The broadest definitions include all intermolecular forces which are electrostatic in origin, namely (2), (3) and (4).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Some authors, whether or not they consider other forces to be of van der Waals type, focus on (3) and (4) as these are the components which act over the longest range.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] All intermolecular/Van der Waals forces are anisotropic (except those between two noble gas atoms), which means that they depend on the relative orientation of the molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The induction and dispersion interactions are always attractive, irrespective of orientation, but the electrostatic interaction changes sign upon rotation of the molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] That is, the electrostatic force can be attractive or repulsive, depending on the mutual orientation of the molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] When molecules are in thermal motion, as they are in the gas and liquid phase, the electrostatic force is averaged out to a large extent because the molecules thermally rotate and thus probe both repulsive and attractive parts of the electrostatic force.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Random thermal motion can disrupt or overcome the electrostatic component of the van der Waals force but the averaging effect is much less pronounced for the attractive induction and dispersion forces.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The Lennard-Jones potential is often used as an approximate model for the isotropic part of a total (repulsion plus attraction) van der Waals force as a function of distance.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces are responsible for certain cases of pressure broadening (van der Waals broadening) of spectral lines and the formation of van der Waals molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The London–van der Waals forces are related to the Casimir effect for dielectric media, the former being the microscopic description of the latter bulk property.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The first detailed calculations of this were done in 1955 by E.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] A more general theory of van der Waals forces has also been developed.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] In low molecular weight alcohols, the hydrogen-bonding properties of their polar hydroxyl group dominate other weaker van der Waals interactions.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] In higher molecular weight alcohols, the properties of the nonpolar hydrocarbon chain(s) dominate and determine their solubility.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Van der Waals forces are also responsible for the weak hydrogen bond interactions between unpolarized dipoles particularly in acid-base aqueous solution and between biological molecules.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] London dispersion forces, named after the German-American physicist Fritz London, are weak intermolecular forces that arise from the interactive forces between instantaneous multipoles in molecules without permanent multipole moments.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] In and between organic molecules the multitude of contacts can lead to larger contribution of dispersive attraction, particularly in the presence of heteroatoms.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] London dispersion forces are also known as 'dispersion forces', 'London forces', or 'instantaneous dipole–induced dipole forces'.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The strength of London dispersion forces is proportional to the polarizability of the molecule, which in turn depends on the total number of electrons and the area over which they are spread.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Hydrocarbons display small dispersive contributions, the presence of heteroatoms lead to increased LDFs as function of their polarizability, e.g. in the sequence RI>RBr>RCl>RF.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] In absence of solvents weakly polarizable hydrocarbons form crystals due to dispersive forces; their sublimation heat is a measure of the dispersive interaction.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] For macroscopic bodies with known volumes and numbers of atoms or molecules per unit volume, the total van der Waals force is often computed based on the "microscopic theory" as the sum over all interacting pairs.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] It is necessary to integrate over the total volume of the object, which makes the calculation dependent on the objects' shapes.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The Van der Waals *force* between two spheres of constant radii (*R*1 and *R*2 are treated as parameters) is then a function of separation since the force on an object is the negative of the derivative of the potential energy function, $\ F_{\rm {VdW}}(z)=-{\frac {d}{dz}}U(z)$ .
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The van der Waals forces between objects with other geometries using the Hamaker model have been published in the literature.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] From the expression above, it is seen that the van der Waals force decreases with decreasing size of bodies (R).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Nevertheless, the strength of inertial forces, such as gravity and drag/lift, decrease to a greater extent.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Consequently, the van der Waals forces become dominant for collections of very small particles such as very fine-grained dry powders (where there are no capillary forces present) even though the force of attraction is smaller in magnitude than it is for larger particles of the same substance.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Such powders are said to be cohesive, meaning they are not as easily fluidized or pneumatically conveyed as their more coarse-grained counterparts.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Generally, free-flow occurs with particles greater than about 250 μm.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The Van der Waals force of adhesion is also dependent on the surface topography.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] If there are surface asperities, or protuberances, that result in a greater total area of contact between two particles or between a particle and a wall, this increases the van der Waals force of attraction as well as the tendency for mechanical interlocking.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] The microscopic theory assumes pairwise additivity.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] It neglects many-body interactions and retardation.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] A more rigorous approach accounting for these effects, called the "macroscopic theory", was developed by Lifshitz in 1956.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Langbein derived a much more cumbersome "exact" expression in 1970 for spherical bodies within the framework of the Lifshitz theory while a simpler macroscopic model approximation had been made by Derjaguin as early as 1934.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Expressions for the Van der Waals forces for many different geometries using the Lifshitz theory have likewise been published.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] There were efforts in 2008 to create a dry glue that exploits the effect, and success was achieved in 2011 to create an adhesive tape on similar grounds (i.e. based on van der Waals forces).
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] In 2011, a paper was published relating the effect to both velcro-like hairs and the presence of lipids in gecko footprints.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] A later study suggested that capillary adhesion might play a role, but that hypothesis has been rejected by more recent studies.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] A 2014 study has shown that gecko adhesion to smooth Teflon and polydimethylsiloxane surfaces is mainly determined by electrostatic interaction (caused by contact electrification), not van der Waals or capillary forces.
[src:pharmacophore-modeling/van-der-waals-force] Among the arthropods, some spiders have similar setae on their scopulae or scopula pads, enabling them to climb or hang upside-down from extremely smooth surfaces such as glass or porcelain.
